          <p><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">cities</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">climate</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">energy</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">energy modeling</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">geospatial</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">metadata</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">model</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">open source software</span><span class="label label-info-sustainability tag link-tag">sustainability</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">utilities</span></p>
          <p>The U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) funded a three-year project, End-Use Load Profiles for the U.S. Building Stock, that culminated in this publicly
available dataset of calibrated and validated 15-minute resolution load profiles for all major residential and commercial building types and end uses,
across all climate regions in the United States. These EULPs were created by calibrating the ResStock and ComStock physics-based building stock models
using many different measured datasets, as described <a href="https://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy22osti/80889.pdf">here</a>.
This dataset includes load profiles for both the baseline building stock and the building </>...</p>
