          <h3><a href="/nasa-modis-t-jpl-l2p-v2019-0/">GHRSST Level 2P Global Sea Surface Skin Temperature from the MODIS on the NASA Terra satellite (GDS2)</a></h3>
          <p><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">atmosphere</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">datacenter</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">earth observation</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">global</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">land</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">marine</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">metadata</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">netcdf</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">oceans</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">orbit</span></p>
          <p>NASA produces skin sea surface temperature (SST) products from the Infrared (IR) channels of the Moderate-resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS) onboard the Terra satellite. Terra was launched by NASA on December 18, 1999, into a sun synchronous, polar orbit with a daylight descending node at 10:30 am, to study the global dynamics of the Earth atmosphere, land and oceans. The MODIS captures data in 36 spectral bands at a variety of spatial resolutions.  Two SST products can be present in these files. The first is a skin SST produced for both day and night observations, derived from the l...</p>
          <p><a href="/nasa-modis-t-jpl-l2p-v2019-0/">Details &rarr;</a></p>
