        <div id="sentinel1-slc-seasia-pds" class="dataset">
          <h3><a href="/sentinel1-slc-seasia-pds/">Sentinel-1 SLC dataset for South and Southeast Asia, Taiwan, Korea and Japan</a></h3>
          <p><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">disaster response</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">earth observation</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">environmental</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">geospatial</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">satellite imagery</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">synthetic aperture radar</span></p>
          <p>The S1 Single Look Complex (SLC) dataset contains Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) data in the C-Band wavelength. The SAR sensors are installed on a two-satellite (Sentinel-1A and Sentinel-1B) constellation orbiting the Earth with a combined revisit time of six days, operated by the European Space Agency. The S1 SLC data are a Level-1 product that collects radar amplitude and phase information in all-weather, day or night conditions, which is ideal for studying natural hazards and emergency response, land applications, oil spill monitoring, sea-ice conditions, and associated climate change effec...</p>
          <p><a href="/sentinel1-slc-seasia-pds/">Details &rarr;</a></p>
          <h4>Usage examples</h4>
          <ul class="dataatwork-list">
          <li>
            <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41597-020-0443-5" class="" target="_none">Rapid flood and damage mapping using synthetic aperture radar in response to Typhoon Hagibis, Japan</a> by Cheryl W. J. Tay, Sang-Ho Yun, Shi Tong Chin, Alok Bhardwaj, Jungkyo Jung &amp; Emma M. Hill</li></a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="https://github.com/earthobservatory/sentinel1-opds/wiki" class="" target="_none">Sentinel-1 Opendataset Wiki and Tutorials</a> by <a href="https://earthobservatory.sg/research-group/geodesy-group-emma-hill/people" target="_none">Earth Observatory of Singapore</a></li></a>
          </li>
        </ul>
