        <div id="wise-neowiser" class="dataset">
          <h3><a href="/wise-neowiser/">NEOWISE Reactivation Data | Near-Earth Object Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer (NEOWISE)</a></h3>
          <p><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">astronomy</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">imaging</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">object detection</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">parquet</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">satellite imagery</span><span class="label label-info tag link-tag">survey</span></p>
          <p>The Near-Earth Object Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer (NEOWISE) is a NASA Medium-class Explorer satellite in low-Earth orbit conducting an all-sky astronomical imaging survey over two infrared bands. The NEOWISE Reactivation mission began in 2013 when the original WISE satellite was brought out of hibernation to learn more about the population of near-Earth objects and comets that could pose an impact hazard to the Earth. The data is also used to study a wide range of astrophysical phenomena in the time domain including brown dwarfs, supernovae and active galactic nuclei.</p>
          <p><a href="/wise-neowiser/">Details &rarr;</a></p>
